      <h2>Why Energy Management Matters</h2>
      <p>
        Solar panels generate power. Batteries store it. Heat pumps use it. But without intelligent control, these systems operate independently — each one making decisions without knowing what the others are doing.
      </p>
      <p>
        A home energy management system (HEMS) connects everything together. It decides when to charge the battery, when to run the heat pump, when to export to the grid, and when to hold energy in reserve — all based on real-time data.
      </p>
      <p>
        The result is <strong>less wasted energy, lower bills, and a home that runs more efficiently</strong> without you having to think about it.
      </p>

      <h2>What We Integrate</h2>
      <p>
        Our automation systems are built around energy — not consumer gadgets. We focus on the systems that actually affect your energy consumption and comfort:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Solar and battery monitoring</strong> — real-time visibility of generation, consumption, and storage</li>
        <li><strong>Heat pump scheduling</strong> — run the heat pump when solar is generating, not when electricity is expensive</li>
        <li><strong>Hydronic heating control</strong> — zone-by-zone temperature management via our ceiling panel system</li>
        <li><strong>Load shifting</strong> — automatically move high-draw appliances (hot water, EV charging) to off-peak or solar-generating hours</li>
        <li><strong>Grid export optimisation</strong> — hold energy when feed-in tariffs are low, export when they're high</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How It Works</h2>
      <p>
        Our systems use MODBUS and other open protocols to communicate between components. A central controller monitors inputs from solar, battery, heat pump, and environmental sensors, then makes decisions based on rules tailored to your household.
      </p>
      <p>
        You can view and adjust settings from your phone or a local display. The system learns your patterns over time and adapts — but you always have manual override.
      </p>

      <h2>Part of a Complete System</h2>
      <p>
        Home automation works best when it's designed alongside the energy systems it controls. That's why we integrate it from the start — not bolt it on afterwards.
      </p>
      <p>
        Our <a href="/laboratory/environmental-service-pod">Environmental Service Pod</a> includes a MODBUS control module as standard, providing centralised management of heat pump, battery, and thermal storage from a single point.
      </p>

